-- Pala operational law
+## Command Center surfaces
+- `Pala Court`: release, push, owner approval, and blocker decisions.
+- `Pala Evidence Ledger`: command, source-card, screenshot, run, and decision proof.
+- `Pala World Standards Atlas`: grouped standards and missing evidence.
+- `Pala Agent Control Radar`: market references such as Codex, Cline, OpenHands, Goose, PR review, and governance tools.
+- `Pala Skill Registry`: skills, adapter/import decisions, and tool boundaries.
+- `Pala Action Queue`: the next blocked or partial actions for the owner/operator.
+
+## User-facing control groups
+- `Governance & Risk`: NIST, ISO, SOC 2, CISA, and risk-management standards.
+- `Application Security`: OWASP web, API, ASVS, MASVS, SAMM, and cheat-sheet coverage.
+- `AI & Agent Governance`: NIST AI RMF, OWASP LLM, OWASP Agentic AI, and MCP allowlist controls.
+- `Supply Chain & Provenance`: SLSA, OpenSSF, Sigstore, in-toto, SBOM, SPDX, CycloneDX, VEX, and GUAC.
+- `Runtime & Platform Security`: Docker, Kubernetes, CIS, Linux, and least-privilege runtime controls.
+- `Threat & Vulnerability Intel`: MITRE ATT&CK, CWE, CAPEC, CVE, CVSS, EPSS, and CISA KEV.
+- `Pala Operating Law`: no-fake-done, source-card gate, owner approval, GitHub boundary, and local evidence.
 
 ## How to use it
 1. Seed the catalog from `sak init`.
@@ -32,3 +40,7 @@ Each standard can carry one or more evidence items:
 3. Inspect the dashboard or `sak status`.
 4. Run `sak cron run` to refresh watcher evidence.
 5. Open `sak court` whenever blocked standards stay unresolved.
+6. Use `/api/control-groups` when another UI or report needs the grouped Command Center state.
+
+## Control rule
+No external tool, repository, or idea becomes a dependency directly. It starts as `reference`, then needs source-card, risk, allowed layer, evidence, Pala Court posture, and owner approval.
